 scrutiny, with much public debate over appropriate criteria. But the question of who gets into Ph.D. programs has by comparison escaped much discussion. That may change with the publication of Inside Graduate Admissions…While the departments reviewed in the book remain secret, the general process used by elite departments would now appear to be more open as a result of Posselt’s book.” —Scott Jaschik, Inside Higher Ed “Revealing…Provide[s] clear, consistent insights into what admissions committees look for.” —Beryl Lieff Benderly, Science  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDiscrimination in higher educationxUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in higher educationzUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxEducation (Higher)xUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 0aTeacher participation in administrationxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aTeacher participation in administrationzUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxFacultyxUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxGraduate workxAdmissionxUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxFaculty. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxGraduate workxAdmission. 7aEDUCATION / Administration / Higher.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063858540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067491564040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674915640423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674915640.jpg  a978-3-11-063858-5  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles